trial-c fit overview

Pawel Sadlowski

trial-c was fit to data preprocessed with RP method C and limited to 10 most popular items. Price shock was scaled by a factor of 4 to roughly match sd=3.

v3b1 model was used with k=30

Runtime ranged 9.6-11h and max memory use was not measured. RDS fit file measures approx. 900MB.

No sampling issues

Sampling problems

pairs( fit, pars = c( 'sigma_lower', 'sigma_upper', 'lp__'))

There’s a solid pull towards homogeneous thresholds, but without divergencies.

pairs( fit, pars = c( 'sigma_gains', 'lp__'))

pairs( fit, pars = c( 'sigma_lpa', 'lp__'))

pairs( fit, pars = c( 'sigma_losses', 'lp__'))

Low \(\hat{R}\) values usually coincide with a low observation count

data$N / data$H
## [1] 6.412162

On average, there are 6-7 observations per customer, which is definitely a low figure considering that there are 12 individual-specific parameters to be estimated. On the other hand, this probably shouldn’t contribute to bad mixing. It could also be caused by low variability in prices, I guess.

all( data$h_id %in% high_rhat)
## [1] FALSE
ggplot( data.frame( ps = as.vector( data$ps[,data$h_id %in% high_rhat]))) +
  geom_density( aes( x = ps), color = 'darkred', lwd = 2) +
  geom_density( data = data.frame( x2 = as.vector( data$ps)), aes( x = x2),
                  fill = 'darkblue', alpha = 0.4) +
  ggtitle( 'Price shock (log diff) distribution for high-Rhat customers (red)') +
  xlab( 'Price shock( log diff)') + ylab( '')

The \(high-\hat{R}\) customers don’t face a distorted distribution of price shocks.

mean( rhat[!is.na( rhat)] > 1.03)
## [1] 0.01191219
rm( high_rhat)

\(\hat{R}\) was higher than 1.03 for approx. 1% of parameters, which isn’t a lot, but is a considerable figure.

Cross-comparison

data.frame( pars = names( rhat),
            rhat = rhat,
            ess_bulk = apply( posterior[,,names( rhat)], 3, ess_bulk),
            ess_tail = apply( posterior[,,names( rhat)], 3, ess_tail)) -> plotdata
rm( ess, rhat)
ggplot( plotdata) +
  geom_point( aes( x = ess_bulk, y = rhat, color = rhat > 1.03)) +
  ggtitle( 'Reltionship between Rhat and Bulk ESS values') +
  xlab( 'Bulk ESS') + ylab( 'Rhat')

ggplot( plotdata) +
  geom_point( aes( x = ess_tail, y = rhat, color = rhat > 1.03)) +
  ggtitle( 'Reltionship between Rhat and Tail ESS values') +
  xlab( 'Tail ESS') + ylab( 'Rhat')

\(\hat{R}\) problems usually coincide with low Bulk ESS, the relationship is not as clear for Tail ESS.
